Text: I got 6 stitches. My parents love my bf and in fact, my mom and him are so close that they go on walks and go to the movies together. I felt uncomfortable and unwanted by his family. To be fair, I was also a little closed off with them but mainly because I felt so unwanted. I have put on some weight, which I am sure his dad noticed because he absolutely hates fat people.

I was never really close to him, our conversations never went past the 'nice weather we're having' area. But I coincidentally ran into him at a bar recently and I initially tried to keep my distance from him because I know he's friends with Zach, but then he told me that not only does he and Zach are no longer in contact with each other, they actually really dislike each other now. I'm guessing something went down after Zach and I broke up. After that, I was more comfortable around him. So, as the night went along and we got drunker, we ended up hooking up.

We are 100% no contact, and have decided we won't talk to each other for at least a few months, or until we're ready to talk and maybe try to be friends. He says he still cares deeply for me and loves me, but this is for the best. I wish it was easier to get over, but it isn't. What advice do y'all have? Thanks!

(Hurt the ego, but whatever, I guess you're not always gonna be the hottest guy she's ever been with.) Then I found another thing that pretty much destroyed me - an e-mail to her high school boyfriend begging him to come visit her and have sex with her, because of how fantastic it was when they used to have sex. This was probably half a year after we had split up, and the implied comparison with me was pretty clear. Making matters worse is that this guy basically checks all the boxes on shit that makes me insecure - tall, douchey rich guy (in contrast to me - 5'8", not at all douchey guy with a good but not incredibly glamorous career). Anyway, these pieces of information - that she pretty much opened up to me sexually only when she felt threatened by another woman, and that she has clearly been with other guys who she's had much more sexual interest in than me - pretty much led me to the alternate hypothesis that it wasn't the vaginal pain and the birth control so much as her lack of attraction to me in comparison to past boyfriends.

I've been with Mike for 4 years now. We have an amazing relationship and I never felt bothered by anything in it, not even silly arguments that are more than common between a couple. Mike has a best friend named Theo. Theo is a cute guy who never seems to settle down, but not in a womanizer way, more like, he hasn't found the one. Well, hadn't found the one.

My Father has been struggling with alcoholism for nearly his entire life, he hasn’t been in contact with myself, my mom, or my sister in years. I guess it all of sudden caught up with him, he past away from a heart attack recently. It still doesn’t feel real, but my girlfriends family has been nothing but supportive throughout the whole thing and helped me grieve through his death. Needless to say, I do not want to attend a funeral or memorial, because I’d like to remember the good times I had with him and not being up bad memories. I had a rough child hood, he cheated on my mother, he wasn’t a great guy.

After meeting last year, Amanda and Isaac became incredibly close and agreed to live together for their Senior year. This past November, Amanda got drunk at a party and ended up making out with a random guy (on Jeff's birthday). Because of this, Amanda told Jeff that she wanted to take a break. Lots of drama. Everyone was shocked because from the outside, Amanda and Jeff seemed to have a really strong relationship (dating for 4+ years).

So I'm getting a cheap apartment, most utilities included, and all maintenance covered. I used the last of my savings for the application fee and hold fee. I'm going to be moving at the end of the month and it's going to be tight, paying the security deposit and prorated rent when I already had to pay lot rent for the trailer this month. I'm selling the trailer at a loss to get about a third of it, selling everything I don't need in the hopes for another third, and I should be able to cover the rest from my paycheck... If I cut the grocery bill.

I'm a freelancer, which means pay isn't always steady. I also have frequent painful and difficult digestive issues as well as migraines that lay me out several times a month. I work hard, I make an effort to save where I can, but some months bills and such wipe me out. I'm just coming through a bout of sick and feeling up to eating again, but thanks to pay waits and bills, I'm broke and down to a bit of brown rice and gelatin in the house. I made a post this morning on r/Random_Acts_of_Pizza and a mod pointed me here for some slightly more substantial help.

In the last year I have developed some health problems. I started having seizures and because of them I had to miss work. Because of that I got fired. I was doing okay still while looking for another job by donating plasma. But my car got repossessed a few days ago and I haven’t been able to get there to donate.

Hi guys, I have PTSD that came from a suicide related incident. I'm not ready to talk about what happened, but it was pretty recent so even the small things are triggering. This timing couldn't possibly be worse, 13 reasons why is gaining popularity incredibly quickly and the ads are popping up everywhere. I'm getting help, but these things take time and I can't just quit the internet. Is there any way I block that specific type of ad?

No place in my city has shelter space for us, and I won't put my baby on the literal street. (I've been there before. Fine for new, but I don't want to have to go through that with a baby). What cities have good shelter programs for homeless mothers and children? I'd love to be able to make some calls and get on a greyhound between the 7th and 16th (when I'll likely be able to get the money to go).
Sometimes I get so angry at her I just hit out. She doesn‚I't push back so it never gets serious. I‚I'm lucky I guess. She knows she‚I's in the wrong.
I saw another text on my boyfriend‚I's phone from his ex. That b***ch‚Ä¶. I know she still wants to hook up with him. So things got heated. He promised me he cut her off. Liar.
I never get into fights at school. I know better. They will expel me again. But after school there have been times I have got into it with this girl I hate.

This girl was running her mouth, saying all these things about me that weren‚I't true. I had to shut her up or everyone would think they could talk trash about me. You have to make sure people know she is full of s**t.

I don‚I't fight anymore. I‚I've grown up. It‚I's not worth it to me anymore, I‚I'm trying to go to college. I‚I'm tired of getting into trouble. Today though, this idiot was running his mouth about my sister and I couldn‚I't stop myself. I had to step up. It was stupid, but she is my sister. He called her the ‚Äúh‚Äù word.

You have to carry a knife or some protection when you live in a neighborhood like mine. What if sh*t starts to go down. I don‚I't want to be the one without something. The part of Flint where I hang ain‚I't Ann Arbor.

I can‚I't believe that I‚I'm the one in here. I‚I'm not the bully. Not like my other friends, they‚I're rough; they‚I're much worse than me. This isn‚I't fair. I just like to make jokes. I am a comedian.

Other kids think I‚I'm tough. They won‚I't mess with me either. Dad said not to put up with any s**t and stand up for yourself. He knows what he‚I's talking about. Nobody would ever mess with me. I would whoop their a**.
I don‚I't do it all the time, I only do it when she makes me mad when, like when she shows off to other boys. Then I have to put the Sheila in her place.

These things happened to me for all of year six and seven and no-one did anything. How come now I‚I'm getting into trouble now for doing the same thing they did to me? Because I‚I'm new here, I‚I'm just showing them they can‚I't mess with me. Once everyone knows I‚I'm not a loser I‚I'll be right. It ain‚I't fair. Nobody helped me out in my old school.

What do you mean I‚I'm responsible? I don‚I't get that it‚I's my fault that other people forwarded the photo. I did it to be funny. She shouldn‚I't have had so much to drink and passed out at the party anyway. She was asking for it. I didn‚I't forward to everyone, just David and maybe one other guy. Plus, she is always showing off her body anyway. She is an exhibitionist. It is David‚I's fault.

I took the photo and posted on the blog, everyone made comments about how weird she looked. That hairdo was crazy; and those shorts. That‚I's not bullying when everyone else makes the comments right? It was meant to be funny. She didn‚I't get it, it was funny. It‚I's not my fault she took it so personally. I didn‚I't know that she would get so upset. Why is everyone so sensitive all the time.
What‚I's the big deal? If I‚I'm such a bully why do I have lots of friends? Nobody likes him. They are happy I put him in his place.
I only sent it once. I know I shouldn‚I't have sent it but it‚I's not like I‚I'm bashing him up. He chose to be gay. People should know. That isn‚I't my problem. It‚I's his.
For the last year, my adolescent son and daughter have been driving me nuts with fighting. I'm at my wits end. How can I get them to stop and get along?

I use to be so happy. No matter what, I always was happy. I got into a relationship with this guy. I love him so much. We‚I're both teenagers. The week after his birthday, my mom made me stop talking to him. It broke me. He came to my house and talked to her, and she let us date again but not see each other. He comes up to my school every day and it tears me apart that I have to lie to her.

My husband took a job out of state for the next year and seems to be a different person. Before, he worked and slept, and on off days, he'd stay home because he didn't want to do anything else. Now he's going out with friends several nights a week while I'm still home working a 50 hours a week job and taking care of two kids by myself. He's suddenly saying he misses me and wants me to be his adored wife, but the whole time, I'm remembering how I've been emotionally starving for the last five years.

I find myself crying over every little thing, like dropping a glass of water. Today, I got out of the shower and noticed that I had forgotten a shirt. I instantly started to cry. When I made it to my room, I began to shake a little, cry more, and I begged for it to stop.

My long-distance girlfriend is in a sorority, and it's changing her. I feel like I'm becoming less important to her and it hurts. She just wants me to support the sorority, but it's so hard. I try every day to show her she's the most important thing to me, but she can't even stay relatively sober at a fraternity party for me so that I won't worry about her doing anything regretful. We love each other, but we're in a rough patch.

My husband always works. He does work from home, but his hours are from morning until night, and he neglects his family. If I have anything I want to do, I have to find a babysitter, but he does what he wants. He rarely comes to bed when I do, and we never have date nights.
Whenever I don't tell my friends or anyone what I did or stuff that's not really important, I feel terrible, like there‚I's a hole in my stomach. It only goes away when I hurt myself.

My husband always works. He does work from home, but his hours are from morning until night, and he neglects his family. If I have anything I want to do, I have to find a babysitter, but he does what he wants. He rarely comes to bed when I do, and we never have date nights.
Whenever I don't tell my friends or anyone what I did or stuff that's not really important, I feel terrible, like there‚I's a hole in my stomach. It only goes away when I hurt myself.

I'm in a long-distance relationship with my ideal man, but I'm not as attracted to him as I should be. Everything else is perfect about him, but I find myself lusting over more attractive men. The next step is marriage, but I want to marry someone who I can wake up to and fall in love with all over again. However, I also don't want to throw away a great relationship over what might just be lust. Am I asking for too much in the "perfect guy"? Is there such a thing? Am I truly in love?
I have no real friends. I have a girlfriend who irritates me but loves me to death. I push her away and pushes me away. We‚I're going through a breakup, and I have nobody.

Back in high school, my friend and I used to masturbate around each other. I hate even talking about it now because it's so weird. We didn't even realize how messed up it was at the time. One time, it escalated and we ended up doing it for each other. It wasn't supposed to be a gay thing, but it sure sounds like it now that I talk about it. I pushed this away until it recently came up in my head again. I'm having a lot of trouble.
I've been struggling with it for a test and I'm starting to believe it's something mental. What could it be?
I have bipolar II disorder, I'm addicted to alcohol and weed, and I'm hopeless. I keep drinking even though it's harming myself and others.
My boyfriend is seeking therapy. He is in his 40s and has some childhood issues. He has kids from his previous ex-wife and is unable to see them.
I have severe anxiety and have tried everything. Everything makes it worst.The only thing that helps is my emotional support animal.

My husband has had issues with alcohol addiction in the past (he'd never admit to this). A while back (3 years ago), I asked him to stop drinking so much, and he agreed. I caught him one night drinking behind my back. I confronted him and he lied, but I told him I knew he was lying because I counted the beers in the fridge and four of them were missing. He admitted and apologized and promised he wouldn't do it again. Lately, my husband has been drinking on and off, but I noticed it was every single night. I didn't like this. For our New Year‚I's resolution, we decided we were going to limit our alcohol consumption. He was on board‚Äîno more drinking every night.

The other night, I counted the beers in the fridge just to see if some were missing. It took a couple of days, but tonight, I discovered a few were missing along with a shot of vodka. He was passed out on the couch when I decided to wake him up and confront him (poor timing, but I couldn't wait). I asked him if he'd come to bed with me (when he drinks, he snores and I cannot sleep‚Äîit's a dead giveaway he's been drinking). He slurred a bit and said no. I asked if he had been drinking, but he snapped and said no. I went into our room to sleep, leaving him on the couch. 

I'm not sure if I'm overreacting or not. I just feel like I'm so honest with him about everything, and I expect the same honesty. He is a good husband in every other regard.

I am divorced and happily remarried. Our blended family of children are in their 20s. My youngest, age 20, continues to call me crazy and favors her dad. He was abusive to me, and I left with injuries. He never wanted kids, and I did. He paid child support only through forced wage earners. Now my daughters favor him after all the sacrifices I made for them the past 15 years as a single mom. I don‚I't deny them a relationship with their dad, but to be called crazy and then watch them hang out with him hurts me to the very core. I‚I'm not sure how to handle this.

I'm in my late 20s, and I've never had a boyfriend or even been on a date. I have no friends. I hate Facebook because everyone else has kids and a great husband and great paying jobs. I work in retail, and I can't find a job. I have an Associate degree. No one is not giving me a chance, and I'm getting upset and frustrated. I feel worthless and feel like everyone hates me. I feel like a failure, and I still live with my Dad. It's very embarrassing!

I've been having this ongoing problem for most of my life now. I am a young adult, and right now, driving and even being a passenger gives me terrible panic attacks and anxiety. I can't ride in the backseat or the front seat with the safety belt on. I have to lean the seat back a bit because the pressure on my back terrifies me. I miss so many opportunities to go places with friends and family because of my fears of having a panic attack. My family offers little to no support. They think it's fake or "all in my head." It makes me feel guilty and at times depressed to the point where I'd rather never wake up anymore. I am not self-harming, I just feel meaningless. This constant fear has taken over my thoughts and my life. I was such a happy person. I want my life back. I want to travel with my friends and family again, but I don't know how. I've almost given up hope on getting better and just accepting the fact that I'll live with this anxiety forever.

My suppose-to-be father told me to go find my real dad. We haven't been getting along since I was a teenager. If I said one thing that he thought was wrong, I always got degraded. He never said ‚ÄúI love you.‚Äù He never gave us hugs. He‚I's always called me horrible names. I feel he's an evil man with no feelings.
I keep being mean to my best friend, and I don't know why all the time. I did come to maybe some kind of conclusion that it is because my mother is mean to me all the time. Could that be a cause?
I've got so much anger. I don't know how to control myself. My girlfriend screams at me all the time, and sometime I don't know how to deal with life. I'm very depressed and angry. I feel lost.
I've been getting told lately by my partner that it‚I's embarrassing that I'm so antisocial around his family and friends. I believe it's because I'm not as social as him.

I met a guy a while ago, and I can't stop thinking about him. I feel like I love him, but I don't think I know him. What if he is not who I think he is? I cry sometimes thinking someone is going to be with him or that he has a girlfriend. I don't know, am I too obsessive? Every time we talk though, it's like magic. He makes me feel amazing, but what if I'm mistaken?

A girl and I were madly in love. We dated for over a year and were even talking about marriage and future plans together. She moved away for school, and we attempted a long distance relationship. We eventually broke up. It's been a year now, and I still haven't lost my feelings for her. I still love her the same way I did. I've suffered from depression ever since the breakup and have been unable to connect with anyone else. It's damaging me and my life.
I would like to be able to have more positive relationships in the present.

My fiance and I have almost the best relationship every girl wants, but lately it's changed. I get less attention and little to no intercourse. He works a lot and goes to the gym a lot (he's a football player for an indoor league), but he has no time for me. We live two hours from family, and when I leave home to see family, he'll text me saying "whatever" and "leave me alone." But when we're together, everything is okay. No fighting or anything. I love this man, but I just don't know what to do anymore.
My dad passed away when I was a teenager. I never got any help, and five years later, I feel like I can't handle it anymore.
My grandma had a stroke and passed away recently. I lost my home and job. I'm looking but haven't found a job. I've been binge watching television and binge eating.

My mother and I have an okay relationship. I know she loves me unconditionally, and I love her the same. However, more times than not, I'm afraid to tell her anything personal because she either doesn't listen, she turns it around and makes everything about her, or she ignores things - even when they are about my mental health.

Me and my adult daughter just do not get along. She's very belittling to me when I don't agree with her. It's almost like she scolds me. We get into all out war. She's said I don't support her in what she does and that I've never loved her. She calls me horrible names, and she pushes my buttons to the point I call her names.

I want a secure relationship with someone that wants to be with me and who will actually put effort into it.
 
 I seem to gravitate toward unavailable men and those that want intimacy and no relationship. I let men dictate and control me because they accuse me of being controlling. I let men emotionally abuse me and I am at their beck and call.
 
 I am not comfortable being alone or doing anything by myself. I feel I need the security of someone being around just to survive. I know what I'm doing wrong and I do it anyway just hoping things will change. How do I stop this behavior and thought process?

My son claims that hes been having extremely violent thoughts and dreams. Not violent like he's hurting someone, but violent thoughts like horrible things happening to his loved ones. He explained one of his dreams the other day and it was so violent it was sickening. It was far beyond anything in a horror movie, he says he can't help these thoughts they just pop up. Please help!

I am in my mid 30s. I feel I have used only 5% of my potential. I am in film making, but everything is stuck. I've never had a serious relationship. I had worthless jobs. I do a lot of meditation to try to fix it.

I constantly feel like everyone is up against me and trying their best to shut me down. It's ruining my mood and even my whole self. I have trouble sleeping, and I keep having sleep paralysis while dreaming of others mocking and judging me.

I've had posttraumatic stress disorder for years without my parents ever finding out. I want to overcome it, but it‚I's so vivid, it‚I's like it‚I's happening again. I'm scared and paranoid. I have depression, which I have been struggling with since a young age.

I have not been able to really sleep. I stay up all times of the night not even knowing why. Every day, I feel like I have anger inside of me. I have a little family, but I can't open up to them like I want to. I have a son, and I feel that I take my anger out on him by screaming at him.

I was anxious to go to middle school. I was afraid of what people might say about me, so when school started, I wasn't acting like myself. I was quiet, which I'm usually not. I didn't talk to anybody and didn't have any friends. Then a few years later, my grandma died. I really became depressed and stop going to school for a little. I hated myself and still do. I just need help. I need someone to care for me. I need someone to show that they care.

I loved him more than anything. He passed away on our anniversary which was also the day I was going to apply for our apartment. I'm not handling it well. I moved to a new town and started a new life but nothing helps.
I self-harm, and I stop for awhile. Then when I see something sad or depressing, I automatically want to self-harm.
Something happened this summer that I cannot forgive myself for. When I think about what happened, I feel ashamed and guilty even though my loved ones forgave me.

About 3 years ago or so I was skinny, but I was still ugly. I really do want to change that but I've tried 3 times. Now can I try but don't stop. At school I get bullied about my weight and my ugliness and I have been bullied my whole life that I believe them.
 How can I stop thinking about them and don't let it get in my head? My parents said I don't weight that much but, they do think I am fat but, they tell me I am not. I told my parents that I need to go to a therapist, but they think I am fine and I think they don't want to deal with it.

I am married to a beautiful lady. I love my wife with all my heart. We have 3 boys and I have a daughter from a previous marriage. We also have 3 grandchildren.
 Now this event is tearing us apart. I want our family to be together and happy. It was a mistake from so long ago. My wife wants to leave and I don't want that to happen I love her so much. Please help me save my marriage. Even my 3 boys want us to work it out. They love us both and want our family together. Please give me some advice or hope. Sincerely heart broken.

I feel that I need to end my present relationship. He lives three hours away and likes the reassurance of having someone to talk to multiple times per day and seeing me once or twice a month. I want someone who is more present and more of a life companion.
 Lately, he has had a very busy work schedule and I have only seen him a few times in the last 6 weeks. I told him that I can't continue in this way because I constantly feel frustrated and angry and that he is not making the relationship enough of a priority. I also feel it is keeping me from possibly finding the relationship I want.
 We have been together 7 years. The problem is that I panic and experience anxiety and depression thinking of him with someone else and then thinking I will never meet someone I like. We have gone through this cycle already 4-5 times and I feel it is unhealthy to stay in it, but my aversion to the anxiety and depression I experience upon separation always leads me to reconcile.

I know someone who is extremely sensitive to stress and very sensitive to a negative tone of voice. Sometimes during a disagreement he tells me that my communication is having a harmful impact on him. Once he believes I am being negative I can't seem to find a better way of communicating. In fact, it is often a self fulling prophesy because his accusatory manner becomes unbearably frustrating. 
 
 
 
 What advice might you offer?
I have manic depression and last summer was very very bad. I have recurring nightmares and I avoid anything that will give me a similar feeling as I did that summer.

My therapist is gay so there are no sexual issues here. However, my therapist for six years has made me believe that he cares about me and that we are friends. I have loaned money to him many times, and he always paid me back.
 
 
 
 I had a medical emergency last weekend and I was heavily medicated. I knew that this therapist came into my home and wrote down my credit card information so he could pay back what he owed me, but this therapist dropped me off and never came again. I don't know what to do.

Tonight, my husband seemed to put our son down through an incorrect approach. His approach was perfectly wrong. I found myself defending my son. I told him that what he did was not the way to encourage our son.
 
 Instead of watching my husband‚I's harsh behavior I decided to sit beside my son and, together, we worked on his science assignment in order to encourage him to study. My husband got upset and he was swearing at me. He threatened me. I knew that he was not joking. His words scared me a lot!

I'm going through a divorce with my wife of three years, who I've known since the 4th grade and been involved with for seven years! We just had a baby seven months ago and never got along with my mother, who I've lived with for years. I am now back with my mother because I have nowhere to go with this divorce looming. I'm heart broken because I fell into a depression, I haven't seen my child in a while, I'm having good and bad dreams, and I feel hated. Can you help? Can you intervene? Can I speak with someone?

Sometimes I can't stop thinking about life after death. I was raised in a religion that teaches that we will live on forever either in hell or in heaven. 
 
 When I think of living forever (even if it is in heaven which should be good), I feel overwhelmed. I don't like the thought of living forever and ever and ever. Sometimes I just can't get the thought out of my mind and the thoughts lead to panic and anxiety. 
 
 Am I crazy? I don't think these thoughts are normal.

It's not entirely true to say I enjoy being sad, but I always find a way to feel that way. I listen to sad music, read tragic stories, and, in a twisted way, like how bad it makes me feel. I focus on negative aspects of my life even if they aren't legitimate or I just make it seem negative.

The sensation lasted hours. It seemed like a circulation problem, and I panicked and of course ended up in the ER again. This time a doctor came to see me immediately. He wanted to talk about my anxiety. He said he could run some more tests, but he didn't think it would help.

I feel like I'm trying to reason my situation though. I'm listing off things that a person would associate success with but I'm not seeing the things I'm failing at. Or maybe I do and the Navy is just exaggerating the things they want out of me? I feel like the Navy is easy and I don't put a lot of time towards it \( I mean qualifications\). When I'm at work I feel like I really  focus in on a task.

I’ve been leaving lights on at night both in the main rooms and my bedroom. The fear is both physical and emotional. I’m so jumpy at work and at home. I feel like I’m seeing things everywhere and little waves of panic wash through me all day. I’m really just finding this incredibly difficult right now and needed to write it out I guess.

During the pregnancy and after the (traumatic) birth of our first child in 2013, symptoms started to intensify, including lots of depression, some manic behavior, and periodic angry outbursts. Somewhere in there we settled on a very (relatively speaking) effective combination of mental health meds that stabilized symptoms. We had our second child in 2015, after which an injury led to the discovery of a debilitating and incurable connective tissue disorder. The symptoms from this have been getting worse since then, and a good chunk of time from 2015 until now has been discovering what’s going on, coming to grips with a new reality, and managing those symptoms. Overall we’ve had a very healthy supportive relationship with strong shared values.

Even moreso with a little push from behind. I've also been interviewing and applying for more secondary jobs to supplement my current employment and that seems to be going increasingly well. Thank you so much again everyone who sent food items to me, I'll be sure to pay it forward someday! EDIT 8/10: I received -even more- stuff just a few days ago, some pasta and sauce and then oatmeal too! Thank you so much, mystery redditor!

Sure it was almost 3 years ago (in July) two months into my first job out of university. I got bit in the leg and continued on like it was nothing. I only fell apart October 2016. I must have been living in survival mode until I got the call that the man who saved my life was getting recognized with a bravery award. Hearing those words, I literally felt my chest rip open and haven't been able to close the wound since.

Hey. First time posting here. I have been living in my car with my brother and cat since May. I am feeling extremely depressed/defeated right now hence why I'm posting here. I'll start from the beginning.

My shift starts at 8 am with equipment checks and drills, often lifting heavy hoses and ladders. Once a call comes in, I could be wrestling with a roaring fire or prying someone out of a wrecked car. The physical demands are extreme and breaks are a luxury that emergencies rarely allow. So, after a long day, rest is a precious commodity, but the alarm could sound at any moment.

As a farmer, my day begins before sunrise. The physical trauma of manual labor - tilling, planting, or harvesting - is a daily reality. Dealing with heavy machinery or stubborn livestock adds to the strain. Lunch breaks are often on the go, a sandwich in one hand and a tool in the other. By sunset, as I make one last check on the animals or the fields, my body screams for rest. But there's solace in knowing that after a good night's sleep, I'll be back at it, tending to the land.

As a construction worker, my day starts at 7am, when we gather at the site for the safety meeting before setting off to the day's tasks. The work demands a lot of physical labor, lifting, digging, climbing ladders, and maneuvering heavy machinery. Despite the physical exertion, the satisfaction of seeing a building taking shape is exhilarating. Yet, the challenges are numerous - the physical toll, the long hours under the sun or in the cold, and the constant need to stay alert to avoid accidents. Most days, it's after sunset when I finally get home, my body aching but my spirit undeterred, ready to do it all over again the next morning.

Training to be a firefighter involves intense physical labor. Our day begins with rigorous workouts that test our endurance and resilience. The physical demands don't stop there, as we're also required to carry heavy equipment, climb stairs in full gear, and practice life-saving techniques. The physical exhaustion can be overwhelming at times, but the thought of being able to save lives and protect our community keeps us going.

Being a farmer requires back-breaking physical labor. From tilling the soil to planting the crops and finally reaping the harvest, each stage demands immense physical strength and stamina. It's not just a matter of working the fields; it's also about maintaining the machinery, repairing fences, and taking care of the livestock. Despite the physical exhaustion, there's a deep sense of satisfaction in growing food and sustaining our communities.

A day in the life of a mover involves a lot of heavy lifting and physical labor. We are tasked with safely and efficiently moving people's belongings, which requires a great deal of strength and coordination. The work is physically demanding, with long hours of carrying heavy furniture and boxes up and down stairs. The bright side is the satisfaction of helping people transition into their new homes, and finishing the day knowing I've completed a hard day’s work.

Work days for a nurse are filled with physical labor that can sometimes go unnoticed. The constant walking, the lifting and moving of patients, the long hours standing on our feet - it's all a part of the job. Despite the physical toll, the reward of helping patients and making a difference in their lives makes it worth the effort. Most days I'm exhausted by the time my shift ends, but the fulfillment I feel is unmatched.

My recent diagnosis with diabetes has brought a significant level of stress into my life. The constant monitoring of my diet, regular insulin shots, and frequent doctor's visits are overwhelming. To make matters worse, my health insurance doesn't cover all my medical costs, and the bills are piling up. The lack of a reliable means of transportation has also made it difficult for me to get to my medical appointments.

I was diagnosed with a chronic illness a few months ago. The medication side-effects are unbearable, causing constant fatigue and dizziness which make it impossible to keep my job. The financial strain is compounding my stress, as I've been forced to sell my vehicle and move into a smaller apartment just to afford my medical expenses.

My life took a downturn when I got diagnosed with a severe heart condition. I was advised against any strenuous activities, which meant I had to quit my job as a construction worker. Navigating through my daily survival without a steady income has been a nightmare, and the loss of my vehicle due to non-payment has made it even more challenging to get to my medical appointments.

Being diagnosed with a serious illness has been a major source of stress in my life. The regular hospital visits, coupled with the physical discomfort, have caused me to take extended leave from work. This has put a strain on my finances and I had to sell my car to cover the medical expenses, making it even harder to attend my regular check-ups.

The diagnosis of my autoimmune disease last year shook me to the core. The pain and discomfort have made it impossible for me to continue working. To make ends meet, I started selling my possessions, including my car. However, without my car, even getting to the hospital for treatment has become a challenge.

As a 15-year-old girl, my hormones are all over the place. I have acne, sudden weight gain and I often have mood swings. Small things trigger me and I end up scratching my arms or legs, anything to distract myself from the mental discomfort. It's not that I have a bad life, but I feel out of control over my emotions. Sometimes it's over small things, like not being able to untangle my necklace.

My health took a turn for the worse when I was diagnosed with chronic kidney disease. I'm now on dialysis and it has taken a toll on my energy levels and overall mood. I had to give up my job, which led to a significant reduction in our family income. We were forced to sell our car to make ends meet, and now my transportation to the dialysis center is a challenge.

I have been battling with heart disease for the past two years. It has disrupted my life completely, requiring frequent hospital visits and medication. I ended up losing my job as I couldn't keep up with the physical demands. This led to a financial crisis and I had to move out of my apartment. Now, I'm living with a friend, trying to manage my health and rebuild my life.

Being diagnosed with cancer was a life-changing event. I had to undergo intense and exhausting treatments, which left me unable to work. The mounting medical bills put immense pressure on me and I had to sell my property to cover the costs. The situation worsened when my insurance denied coverage for certain treatments. Now, I'm struggling to afford the cost of living while battling this disease.

My life took a downward spiral when I was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. The constant pain and fatigue made it impossible for me to continue my job. My unemployment led to financial difficulties and I had to let go of my vehicle. Now, getting to my medical appointments has become a struggle, making it even more challenging to manage my illness.
My dietary stress has been causing me to crave junk food more often than not, and even though I know it's harming my body, I can't seem to resist the temptation.
My obsession with counting calories and skipping meals has been taking a toll on my health, but I can't seem to stop, even though I'm aware of the damage it can cause.
Lately, I've been on this restrictive diet to get fit, and even though I feel lightheaded most of the time, I keep pushing myself believing it's the right thing to do.
I've been surviving on junk food for quite some time now because of my hectic schedule, and I can feel my energy levels plummeting day by day.
Despite my stomach constantly growling with hunger, I have been ignoring it due to my fear of gaining weight and this has caused me to feel weak and fatigued.

Recently, my skin has become dull and dry despite my usual skincare regime. With the scorching heat in my area, it's possible that dehydration might be taking a toll on me, subtly wreaking havoc on my skin. I had high hopes from my skincare products but they seem to be falling short. If anyone has any insights or remedies for this, I would be really grateful.
Skipping meals due to my hectic work schedule has become a norm, causing a significant change in my energy and focus throughout the day.
My recent obsession with counting calories and a fear of gaining weight has led me to cut out many essential nutrients from my diet.
I've been so engrossed in my workload, I hardly have time for proper meals, instead, I've been surviving on coffee and junk food.
My attempt to lose weight rapidly made me fall into the trap of fad diets, leading to an imbalance of vital nutrients in my body.
Too much takeaway and processed food has become my go-to due to lack of time to prepare home-cooked meals, making me feel sluggish and drained.

1. He was always so sensitive that it worried me. He would retreat into his room for hours, completely overwhelmed by his emotions, and I would be left picking up the pieces. I remember this one time, he had a major meltdown over a trivial argument, and in his rage, he threw a glass at the wall. I was left to clean up the broken shards, my heart aching for his emotional turmoil. The police came that day to check on the noise, and I had to show them the shattered glass as evidence.

2. She was a hurricane of emotions, constantly blowing hot and cold. One moment she would be laughing, the next she would be in tears. I recall a night when we were watching a movie, and she suddenly began to sob, wailing about how the end reminded her of her past. She gripped my arm so tightly, her nails dug into my skin. The next day, I had to show the doctor my bruises, just to make sure everything was okay.

3. He was a puzzle of raw, unchecked emotion. One afternoon, after a particularly painful conversation, he threw himself into a fit of rage. He destroyed the living room, throwing furniture around, and when I tried to stop him, he scratched my face. It was a sight that I had to show to the policemen who came to investigate the disturbance, my face bruised and scratched from his emotional outburst.

4. She was a bundle of explosive emotions. It was like walking on eggshells around her, never knowing when she would erupt. In one such instance, she lost control and flung a vase across the room, narrowly missing me. She attacked me too, and left behind nail marks on my arms. I had to show these marks to the police when they arrived, responding to a noise complaint from the neighbors.

5. It was like living inside a storm, his emotions were always running high. I remember this one incident when he lost control over a minor disagreement about dinner. He threw plates and cups, and when I tried to calm him, he lashed out at me, leaving deep scratches on my arms. I had to show these wounds to the police when they came, called upon by our frightened neighbors.

Emotional stress has become my constant companion ever since the painful breakup with my girlfriend. I remember the last time we met, her eyes welled up with tears, the sharp sting of her words still echoing in my ears. The misery of losing her, the emptiness, and the constant questioning of my self-worth has left me emotionally drained. Sleep eludes me, as I toss and turn thinking about her. I've tried to push the thoughts away, but they keep creeping back in, causing more emotional damage than I can bear.

He was always a sensitive soul, taking things to heart a little too easily. My words, even though they were meant to be constructive, seemed to hurt him more than help. There was this one incident, where he locked himself in his room for a week, refusing to talk to anyone after a heated argument we had. He was emotionally stressed, with tears surfacing every now and then. The look in his eyes was enough for anyone to understand the emotional turmoil he was going through.

She was always a perfectionist, wanting everything to be just right. Her room had to be spotless, her work had to be exemplary, and her relationships had to be flawless. But the world is not a perfect place, and when things didn't go as planned, she would break down. I remember her sobbing inconsolably when she scored less than she expected in her exams. The emotional stress it caused her was visible in her red, swollen eyes.

My friend was always the life of the party, but behind the laughter, there was hidden pain. His parents' divorce had hit him hard, causing emotional stress that he found hard to cope with. I remember one night, after everyone else had left, he broke down and cried. He tried to hide his tears with a fake smile, but his emotions were too raw to hide.

She was always cheerful and bubbly, but things changed after her dog died. Her constant companion was gone, leaving a void that she struggled to fill. You could see her trying to hold back her tears whenever someone mentioned her pet. The emotional stress was etched on her face, reflecting her inner turmoil.

Lately, I've been feeling overwhelmed with the amount of information I need to process at work. It's as if time is moving too quickly, I'm constantly apprehensive and burdened by guilt. My standards for myself are becoming unbearably high, leading to self-criticism and in the worst moments, self-loathing.

The panic attacks come out of nowhere, leaving me gasping for breath and terrified. I don't feel like myself anymore, and sometimes, the world around me doesn't even seem real. It's as if I've completely lost control over my life.

I can't shake off the intense feelings of jealousy and resentment, they're consuming my every thought. I'm attached to things and people that only bring me pain. My self-esteem is at an all-time low, and this unattainable pursuit of perfectionism is driving me to the edge.

My mind is a whirl of worries and fears that I can't quieten. The guilt of past mistakes weighs heavily on my heart, and no matter how hard I try, I can't let go. I'm constantly second-guessing myself, criticizing every decision I make. It feels as if I'm spiraling, losing control of my own thoughts and actions.

Sometimes I feel an intense rush of anxiety, a panic attack that leaves me shaky and disoriented. I've become overly critical of myself, setting impossible standards that I can never meet. I'm losing my sense of self, grappling with feelings of unreality, and the constant sense of being out of control is terrifying.

Just recently I've started to feel as though the days are rushing by, taking me along in their unyielding torrent. It's as if my mind is constantly bombarded with information, thoughts, and anxieties that I can't seem to process fast enough. It's like I'm constantly on the edge of a panic attack, a sensation that's both terrifying and exhausting.

The past few months have been characterized by a profound sense of guilt and shame. I feel as if I'm constantly criticizing myself, fueled by my own unattainable standards of perfection. No matter how much I try, there's just this persistent feeling of being out of control, like I'm passively watching my life unspool from a distance.

I've been having a hard time lately, feeling as if I'm not myself. There's this strange detachment, like I'm a spectator in my own life, and an equally unsettling sense of things not being real. It's as if I'm constantly fighting some internal battle, a struggle that leaves me feeling utterly drained.

Lately, I've been feeling like I'm in a constant state of worry, hounded by feelings of jealousy and resentment that I can't seem to let go of. Sometimes, it feels like I'm spiraling out of control, as though my life is governed by some unseen force that keeps pushing me towards the edge.

My mind feels like it's constantly under siege. The barrage of thoughts, concerns, and anxieties seem to come in waves, leaving me feeling overwhelmed and out of control. It's as though I'm a prisoner to my own insecurities, dragged along by an unending current of self-loathing and criticism.

Always being the responsible one, needing to fix everything and everyone, can wear you down. You start to see the world through a lens of problems to be solved, and it's exhausting. The emotional toll of always being the caretaker can be overwhelming. You start to believe that if you're not fixing things, you're not valuable. It's important to remember that your worth isn't dependent on others, but it's a perspective that's tough to shake.

The pressure to conform to societal norms can be immense. Expected to fit into certain roles and act in certain ways, it feels like stepping out of line is more trouble than it's worth. You're so worried about being judged and rejected that you start to live a life that doesn't feel like your own. You forget your own truth, your own desires, just to fit in and feel accepted.

The story you tell yourself, about who you are and what you're capable of, can be a constant source of self-doubt and anxiety. It feels like you're in a box, with no room to grow or change, and it's stifling. You start to believe that this is all you'll ever be, and it's a bleak outlook. It's crucial to remember that you're more than the sum of your past mistakes and failures.

A negative attitude can color your entire view of the world. Everything looks grim and hopeless, and it feels like there's no point in trying. This belief solidifies into a self-fulfilling prophecy, and you end up stuck in a cycle of negativity and despair. It's a constant struggle to break free from this mindset, but it's important to remember that there's always another perspective to consider.

A rigid world view can make you feel trapped. You see things in black and white, with no room for shades of grey. It feels like there's only one right way to live, one right way to be, and anything else is wrong and shameful. This belief can be isolating, making you feel alone and misunderstood. It's a challenging belief to question and change, but it's necessary for personal growth and happiness.

Sometimes, drawn in by the narrative spun by the tormentor, victims may start to believe that their tormentor's abusive actions are somehow justified due to their own failings. This misguided belief begins to shape their worldview and they may even start to blame themselves for the torment they are experiencing. In reality, the victim is not at fault, but the abuser's manipulation can make it seem this way.

The emotional turbulence that ensues as a result of abuse can cause victims to question their own roles in the relationship. The abuser may switch between kind and cruel behaviour, making the victim feel like they are responsible for the abuser's good behaviour. In their desperate search for safety and comfort, they may start to believe that they need to change or behave in certain ways to ensure the abuser's kindness.

In abusive situations, the victim may start to view their existence through the lens of the abuser's actions. They may even think that their survival is dependent on them meeting the abuser's demands, no matter how unreasonable they may be. This distorted view of reality can be incredibly dangerous, as it can undermine the victim's sense of self and self-worth.

The victim's attitudes towards themselves and the world around them can be heavily influenced by the constant abuse. They may start to believe that they deserve the abuse, or that it's a normal part of life. These misguided beliefs can prevent them from seeking help and escaping the abusive situation.

In some cases, the victim may even start to rewrite their own stories to accommodate the abuser's actions. They may convince themselves that they are not victims but are instead part of a "normal" relationship, wherein the abuser's behaviour is justified. This warped narrative can prevent them from recognising the reality of their situation and seeking help.

I've been dating my partner for a year now, and he's changed a lot since we first met. He used to be the life of the party, always out with friends and enjoying his time. But he has become more introverted, preferring to spend his time alone or with me, which I find slightly suffocating. He says he loves me and wants to settle down, but his new attitude makes me wonder if this is the same person I fell in love with.

My wife recently got a promotion at work, and I'm incredibly proud of her. But things haven't been the same at home. She often brings her work back home and is constantly on her laptop or on calls. I feel like a single parent, taking care of our two kids while she's locked up in her home office. She assures me that it's a temporary thing, but it's hard not to feel neglected.

I've been taking care of my elderly mother for the past three years. As her health declines, she becomes more dependent on me, and it's harder for me to maintain a life outside of caregiving. My friends invite me out, but I often have to decline because I'm too worried about leaving her alone. I feel like I'm losing my identity and becoming just a caregiver.

My son recently came out to me as gay. I love him and want to support him, but I'm struggling to reconcile this with my own beliefs. I was raised in a conservative family where homosexuality was not accepted. I want to be there for my son, but I'm finding it hard to let go of my old views.

My best friend has developed a drug addiction. It's heartbreaking to see someone I care about fall into such a destructive cycle. I've tried to help him, but he refuses to acknowledge the problem. It's frustrating and draining, and I don't know how much longer I can keep trying to save him from himself.

My sister and I used to be so close, she was my confidante in everything. Yet, ever since she moved out west and started her new job, it feels like we live in different worlds. Our daily talks have now turned into monthly, sometimes bimonthly catch ups. She's so engrossed in her new lifestyle and her new friends, it feels like she doesn't need me in her life anymore. I feel like an outsider, a stranger to her world, all alone in the world we once shared together.

In the beginning, he was the funny, charming guy that I fell in love with. He would always make sure I was cared for and would go out of his way to make me happy. But now, he's become this person who is always busy, always working, always too tired to spend time with me. I can't remember the last time he asked me how my day was or the last time we had a proper conversation. I feel neglected, like I'm just an afterthought in his life.

My best friend and I have been inseparable since we were kids, but ever since she got married, things have changed. She's always busy with her husband and her new life, and it seems like there's no room for me anymore. I miss the old times when we would hang out and share everything, now it feels like I'm just intruding in her life.

I used to look up to my father and admire him for everything he has achieved. He was my role model, my hero. But recently, I found out some truths about him that have shattered my image of him. He's not the man I thought he was and I feel betrayed, like the person I admired was just a façade.

My wife used to be my rock, always there for me when I needed her. Now it feels like she's more interested in her career than our marriage. She's always working late, always too tired to talk, always too busy to spend time with me. It feels like I'm living with a stranger, not the woman I married. I feel alone and neglected, like I'm just a burden to her.

It's tough to swallow, but the truth is, during my darkest hours, I found myself solely dependent on myself. Despite reaching out to those I thought I could trust, their lives were too busy to step in and lend a hand. It's a hurtful reality, but it's my reality - that in my struggles, I am alone.

As I hit rock bottom, I yearned for a shoulder to lean on, only to realize that I had no one to turn to. The friends I had confided in previously seem to be too occupied with their own lives to offer me a momentary solace. The feeling of being alone in a crowd is more painful than the problem itself.

In my time of need, I felt the sting of solitude. Those I considered friends, those I had supported in times of need, were nowhere to be found when the tables turned. It's a hard pill to swallow, acknowledging the fact that the many relationships I had nurtured, were not there to nurture me in return.

It's disheartening, realizing that I'm alone in my fight. I've reached out to those I trusted, those I've helped before, only to be met with silence. It's a bitter taste, understanding that when the chips are down, I only have myself to rely on.

During my toughest times, I learned that the people I thought I could trust weren't available to be there for me. Despite my efforts to connect, I found myself alone. It's a harsh reality check, realizing that I have to face my challenges on my own, even after all the times I've been there for others.

It's a strange feeling, to find myself wrapped in solitude, even in a crowd. There were times when I was surrounded by people who claimed to understand, who said they were there for me. But when I reached out during my darkest hours, silence was the only answer I received. It's a sobering realization - everyone is caught up in their own whirlwinds, too busy to spare a moment, let alone a shoulder to lean on.

The loneliness sinks in when you realize that there's no one there to pick up the pieces. I've had conversations with friends about struggles and strife, only to find these same friends missing when I'm battling my own crises. It shatters my heart anew each time I come to the understanding that these people, these 'friends', have their own lives to live, their own battles to fight.

In moments of profound despair, I've reached out, only to grasp at air. Where were those who pledged to be by my side? Those who swore they would support me through thick and thin? I cannot blame them, for they too have their own lives to lead, their own challenges to face. But it doesn't take the sting out of the loneliness I feel.

My heart sinks as I reach out to those I've confided in before, only to find them unresponsive. It's not their fault, everyone has their own lives to lead, their own problems to solve. Yet, the pain of realizing that you're truly alone, that there is no one who will be there for you in your time of need, is a bitter pill to swallow.

I've tried to reach out, to find comfort in the presence of friends, but the harsh reality is that they too have their own struggles to contend with. The realization strikes like a hard blow, leaving me breathless and alone. I understand, life goes on and people can't always be there for you. Yet, it doesn't soothe the sharp sting of loneliness.

Being confined to a hospital bed is no joke. I recently underwent an intense kidney surgery due to infection, and the journey to recovery is tougher than I anticipated. I'm trying to use this time constructively by prepping for my grad school entrance exams, but it's a tremendous strain on me, both physically and mentally. My only consolation is that my diligence will eventually bear fruit.

The routine kicks off early in the morning, just as the world begins to stir. Colleagues and I arrive promptly at dawn to guide the day's operations. The task at hand is challenging, particularly given our limited manpower, but it's a challenge that I relish. We find ourselves deep in the thick of it, working tirelessly to prepare our massive, sprawling facility for the day ahead. Despite the immense scale of the operation, there's an unspoken beauty in rolling up your sleeves and getting stuck in the trenches.
I once found myself in a phase where the spiritual beliefs that used to guide me seemed to lose their significance. It was emotionally draining and seemed like a dark tunnel with no visible end.

During a particularly challenging time in my life, I felt as though the divine connection I had always relied on was no longer there for me. The comfort and peace I derived from my spiritual practices seemed to have evaporated, leaving me feeling lost and adrift.
There was a time when I questioned every religious teaching I had ever been given, the doctrines that had once given my life direction and purpose suddenly felt hollow and unconvincing.

I remember feeling as though my spiritual anchor had slipped from the seabed and I was adrift in a vast, unknown sea. The familiar touchstones were no longer there; I had to face the chilling wind of uncertainty alone.

This profound sense of disconnect from my spiritual roots was both disorienting and distressing to me. I felt like I was wandering in a desert, yearning for the oasis of spiritual comfort that was once so integral to my life.

There came a time when the religious tenets I had once held dear seemed to carry no weight or resonance. It was as if I were looking at the world through a new lens, one devoid of the spiritual clarity I had once cherished.

For a while, I found myself in a spiritual wilderness, devoid of the beliefs that had once provided me solace. I felt like a boat without a compass, navigating through life’s stormy seas with no guiding star.
It was a disturbing phase of my life where the religious principles I had always leaned on no longer provided support. I felt as though I was walking a tightrope with no safety net beneath me.

I went through a period where the serenity and guidance I used to derive from my faith seemed to have evaporated. It felt like stumbling blindfolded through an uncharted territory, hoping to find my way back to clarity and peace.

There was a phase when the spiritual compass that had once guided me seemed to fail. I felt disoriented, like a ship in a foggy sea, unable to see the lighthouse that had always directed me to the safe shore.
